A narrow cobblestone path winds through an old cemetery veiled in thick blue-grey fog. The stones glisten with recent rain, reflecting a dim series of orange streetlamps that stretch into the mist. Each lamp flickers weakly, shrouded in tattered black vines that hang like decaying lace. Statues of angels and mourners stand along the path, their features softened and hollowed by time, their silhouettes barely visible through the haze. Crosses and gravestones jut from the ground in uneven rows, some toppled, others half-swallowed by moss and shadow. The air feels damp, timeless, and heavy with a spectral quiet, as though the world has forgotten this place but the dead have not. The faint glow of a single lantern—gripped by a weathered statue—casts a lonely warmth into the chill mist, its light trembling as though alive.
